        "content": "[ID: tool_7f6deb4893df735e]\nFile: /Users/bill/projects/forge/runtime/design.md (118 lines)\n\n# Runtime Module Design\n\n## Executive Summary\n\nThe `runtime` module provides the foundational C runtime library required by the Forge compiler's C backend. It is implemented as a passive, header-only library that establishes the memory layout and operational semantics for Forge's high-level constructs in a C environment. By providing a suite of macros and inline functions, the runtime enables the C backend to transform complex Forge features—such as dynamic slices, length-prefixed strings, optional types, error results, tagged unions, and concurrency primitives—into efficient and readable C code. Its primary goal is to bridge the gap between Forge's expressive type system and C's low-level primitives while maintaining semantic equivalence and providing a robust execution environment.\n\n## File Inventory\n\n- [forge_runtime.h](forge_runtime.h): The core runtime header. It contains all macro definitions, type structures, and inline helper functions that constitute the Forge execution environment for C targets. It defines the fundamental data structures for slices, strings, optionals, and results, as well as the logic for concurrency and file I/O.\n\n## Architecture and Data Flow\n\nThe `runtime` module is a passive component that does not maintain internal state or have an independent execution flow. Instead, it acts as a contract and a toolkit for the code generated by the [LIR module](../pkg/lir/design.md).\n\nThe architecture leverages C macros to implement a form of \"template-based\" type generation. Since C lacks native support for generics, the Forge C backend uses these macros to define concrete, specialized struct types for every unique instantiation of a generic Forge type (e.g., `Slice_int32_t`, `Opt_string`, or `Chan_int32_t`). This approach ensures type safety at the C level and allows the compiler to generate code that is tailored to specific data types. Data flows through these structures as they are passed between functions, with the runtime providing the logic for common operations like resizing slices, wrapping values in optional containers, or managing thread-safe communication through channels.\n\n## Interface Implementations\n\nAs a C header library, this module does not implement any Go interfaces. It serves as the target execution environment for the C code generator within the [LIR module](../pkg/lir/design.md).\n\n## Public API\n\nThe Public API of the runtime consists of the macros and inline functions intended to be utilized by the Forge-generated C code. These are categorized by the Forge language features they support.\n\n### Dynamic Slices\nForge slices are implemented as dynamic arrays with automatic resizing capabilities and support for sub-slicing.\n- `FORGE_SLICE_DEF(ElemType, SliceName)`: A macro that defines a struct containing a pointer to the data, the current length, and the total capacity.\n- `forge_slice_empty(SliceName)`: Initializes a slice structure to an empty state (null data, zero length and capacity).\n- `forge_push(slice_ptr, elem, SliceName)`: Appends an element to the slice. If the length reaches the capacity, it performs a geometric resize (doubling the capacity) using `realloc`.\n- `forge_pop(slice_ptr)`: Removes and returns the last element of the slice. The caller is responsible for ensuring the slice is not empty.\n- `forge_subslice(slice, low, high, SliceName)`: Creates a new slice view representing the range `[low, high)`. This view shares the underlying data pointer with the original slice.\n- `forge_slice_lit(SliceName, ElemType, ...)`: A convenience macro that creates a new slice from a C initializer list, allocating heap memory for the contents.\n- `forge_contains(slice, elem)`: Performs a linear search through the slice to determine if a specific element is present.\n\n### Strings\nStrings in Forge are implemented as length-prefixed byte slices (`forge_string`), which is an alias for `ForgeSlice_uint8_t`. This allows strings to contain embedded null bytes and ensures that length-related operations are O(1).\n- `FORGE_STR(lit)`: A macro to create a `forge_string` from a C string literal at compile-time.\n- `forge_str_from_cstr(cstr)`: Creates a `forge_string` from a null-terminated C string, copying the data to the heap.\n- `forge_str_from_bytes(data, len)`: Creates a `forge_string` from raw bytes, copying them to the heap and adding a hidden trailing null for C interop.\n- `forge_str_eq(a, b)`: Performs a length-aware equality check.\n- `forge_str_cmp(a, b)`: Performs a lexicographic comparison.\n- `forge_str_concat(a, b)`: Concatenates two strings into a new heap-allocated `forge_string`.\n- `forge_str_contains`, `forge_str_index_of`, `forge_str_has_prefix`, `forge_str_has_suffix`: Length-aware string searching and prefix/suffix checks.\n- `forge_str_replace`, `forge_str_repeat`, `forge_str_join`: High-level string transformations that return new heap-allocated strings.\n- `forge_str_trim`: Returns a new string with leading and trailing whitespace removed.\n- `forge_fprint_str(file, s)`: Writes a `forge_string` to a `FILE*` in a length-aware manner.\n\n### Optional Types\nOptional types (`T?`) are represented as a struct containing a boolean flag (`has`) and the actual value.\n- `FORGE_OPT_DEF(ElemType, OptName)`: Defines a specialized optional struct for a given type.\n- `forge_some(value, OptName)`: Wraps a concrete value into an optional struct with the `has` flag set to true.\n- `forge_none(OptName)`: Returns an optional struct with the `has` flag set to false.\n- `forge_isnull(opt)`: A helper to check if an optional value is empty.\n- `forge_unwrap(opt)`: Extracts the value from an optional. This should only be called after verifying the value exists.\n\n### Error Results\nForge's idiomatic `(T, error)` return pattern is mapped to a result struct in C.\n- `FORGE_RESULT_DEF(ElemType, ResultName)`: Defines a result struct containing a success value, an error message (`const char*`), and a boolean `is_err` flag.\n- `forge_ok(val, ResultName)`: Constructs a successful result containing the provided value.\n- `forge_err(msg, ResultName)`: Constructs an error result containing the provided error message.\n- `forge_is_err(r)`: Checks if a result represents a failure.\n\n### Concurrency Primitives\nThe runtime provides support for Forge's concurrency model using POSIX threads (pthreads).\n- `FORGE_CHAN_DEF(ElemType, ChanName)`: Defines a thread-safe, buffered or unbuffered channel structure.\n- `FORGE_CHAN_IMPL(ElemType, ChanName, Suffix)`: Generates the implementation functions for a specific channel type, including `make`, `send`, `recv`, `close`, and `free`.\n- `forge_spawn(func, arg)`: Launches a function in a new detached thread, implementing the Forge `spawn` keyword.\n\n### Utility Helpers\n- `forge_hash_string`: Implements the FNV-1a hashing algorithm for strings.\n- `forge_sprintf`: A wrapper around `vsnprintf` that automatically calculates the required size and returns a heap-allocated formatted string.\n- `forge_bool_str`: Returns \"true\" or \"false\" for a boolean value.\n- `forge_toupper`, `forge_tolower`: Convert strings to upper or lower case, returning new heap-allocated strings.\n- `forge_char_to_string`: Converts a single character (uint8_t) to a heap-allocated string.\n- `forge_read_file`: Reads an entire file into a heap-allocated string, returning a `forge_str_bool_t` struct.\n- `forge_write_file`: Writes a string to a file, returning a boolean indicating success.\n- `forge_getwd`: Returns the current working directory.\n- `forge_path_dir`, `forge_path_base`, `forge_path_ext`: Utilities for working with file paths.\n- `forge_itoa`: Converts an `int64_t` to a heap-allocated string.\n- `forge_atoi`: Parses a string into an `int64_t`, returning a `forge_atoi_result` struct.\n- `forge_parse_float`: Parses a string into a `double`, returning a `forge_parse_float_result` struct.\n\n### Tagged Unions\nFor ad-hoc union types (e.g., `string | i32`), the runtime provides a generic `ForgeUnion` struct.\n- `ForgeUnion`: A struct containing an integer tag and a union of supported Forge types (i32, i64, f32, f64, bool, string, and pointers).\n- `FORGE_UNION_TAG_*`: Constants for identifying the active member of a `ForgeUnion`.\n- `forge_union_i32`, `forge_union_string`, etc.: Specialized constructor functions that initialize a `ForgeUnion` with the correct tag and value.\n\n## Implementation Details\n\n### Memory Management\nThe runtime currently utilizes the standard C library's `malloc`, `realloc`, and `free` for memory management. A critical implementation detail is that the runtime does not yet include a garbage collector. Consequently, heap-allocated objects—including slices, strings created by helper functions, and class instances—are currently leaked during execution. This is a known limitation that is acceptable for short-lived compiler tasks but will require a GC (such as Boehm-Demers-Weiser) for broader use.\n\n### Slice Growth Strategy\nThe `forge_push` macro implements a geometric growth strategy to ensure amortized O(1) append operations. When a slice's length reaches its capacity, the capacity is doubled. If the slice was previously empty, it is initialized with a default capacity of 4. This minimizes the number of reallocations required as a slice grows.\n\n### String Handling\nStrings in the Forge C runtime are represented by the `forge_string` struct, which contains a pointer to the data and its length. This design allows for O(1) length retrieval and supports strings with embedded null bytes. For compatibility with standard C functions that expect null-terminated strings, heap-allocated `forge_string` objects carry a hidden trailing `\\0` byte immediately following the data. This trailing byte is not included in the `.len` field.\n\n### Concurrency Implementation\nChannels are implemented using a circular buffer protected by a `pthread_mutex_t`. Two condition variables (`not_empty` and `not_full`) are used to manage blocking send and receive operations. `forge_spawn` uses `pthread_create` and `pthread_detach` to provide fire-and-forget thread execution.\n\n### Tagged Union Dispatch\nThe `ForgeUnion` type uses an integer tag to identify the active member of its internal union. This allows the generated C code to perform safe type dispatching (e.g., in `match` statements) by checking the tag before accessing the union's data.\n\n## Dependencies\n\n- **Standard C Library**: The runtime depends on standard headers including `\u003cstdio.h\u003e`, `\u003cstdlib.h\u003e`, `\u003cstdint.h\u003e`, `\u003cstdbool.h\u003e`, `\u003cstring.h\u003e`, `\u003cstdarg.h\u003e`, `\u003cctype.h\u003e`, and `\u003cunistd.h\u003e`.\n- **POSIX Threads**: The concurrency primitives require the `pthread` library.\n- **LIR Module**: This module is a critical dependency for the C backend in [pkg/lir](../pkg/lir/design.md), which relies on the macros and types defined here to emit valid C code.\n\n## Technical Debt and Future Work\n\n- **Garbage Collection**: Integrating a garbage collector is the highest priority to prevent memory leaks in long-running Forge programs compiled to C.\n- **Map Implementation**: A robust hash map implementation is required to support Forge's `map\u003cK, V\u003e` type in the C backend.\n- **Error Handling Refinement**: The current error result uses a simple string for error messages. This should be expanded to support more complex, structured error types as the language evolves.\n- **Thread Safety**: While channels are thread-safe, other runtime primitives (like slices) are not and will require synchronization if shared across threads.\n",
